We found that three of our four traits had a strong relationship with photoperiod, but not always in the direction we predicted. Taller species with larger trunk diameters and leaves with high nitrogen content had larger responses with longer photoperiods (Fig. \ref{fig:traitSlopes} c, i, o; Tables \ref{tabHt}, \ref{tabDBH}, \ref{tabLNC}). But, contrary to our expectation, species with denser, high leaf mass area leaves had smaller photoperiod responses, allowing them to potentially budburst under shorter photoperiods (Fig. \ref{fig:traitSlopes}f).\\

% paragraph on chilling and forcing
Temperature cues ($\beta_{\text{trait.chilling}}$ and $\beta_{\text{trait.forcing}}$) exhibited no relationships with individual traits, but by accounting for the effects of leaf or wood traits, we found the importance of our three cues on budburst to vary by trait. Of the three cues, chilling ($\beta_{\text{chilling}}$) was the strongest in our models of height (\Sexpr{htMuCSpMean} days per standardized chill portions, UI: \Sexpr{lower_htMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_htMuCSpMean}), diameter (\Sexpr{dbhMuCSpMean} days per standardized chill portions, UI: \Sexpr{lower_dbhMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_dbhMuCSpMean}), wood stem density (\Sexpr{ssdMuCSpMean} days per standardized chill portions, UI: \Sexpr{lower_ssdMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_ssdMuCSpMean}), and leaf nitrogen content (\Sexpr{lncMuCSpMean} days per standardized chill portions, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lncMuCSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lncMuCSpMean}), with more chilling advancing budburst. Our model of leaf mass area, however, estimated photoperiod as the strongest cue ($\beta_{\text{photoperiod}}$, \Sexpr{lmaMuPSpMean} days per standardized photoperiod, UI: \Sexpr{lower_lmaMuPSpMean}, \Sexpr{upper_lmaMuPSpMean}). After accounting for the effects of traits, only our height and diameter model found all three environmental cues to drive budburst timing (Tables \ref{tabHt}, \ref{tabDBH}). Our models of wood stem density and leaf nitrogen content in turn found temperature cues alone to shape budburst (Tables \ref{tabSSD}, \ref{tabLNC}), while our model of leaf mass area found a large response to only photoperiod (Table \ref{tabLMA}).\\

